g that it won't cause meltdowns, it leaves practically no nuclear waste (and none whatsoever if the right elements are used), and <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>    it really isn't suitable for the production of bomb-grade materials.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> ... Of course fusion isn't practical yet<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I don't think I have ever seen anyone with a violent sentiment one way or another in reference to fusion power.<br>
<br>
More importantly, &quot;it really isn't suitable for the production of bomb-grade materials&quot;, is simply untrue. Fusion reactors are magnifcant at producing the highest quality weapons material.<br>
A fusion reactor can breed 2 atomic bombs per year per every square yard of surface area of the inner wall (&quot;first wall&quot;).<br>
Take a look at a picture of a fusion reactor (which are small compared to a real powerplant requirement). There's a heck of a lot of square yards!<br>
<br>
This is a picture of &quot;JET&quot;, MUCH smaller than a powerplant system:<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.sciencemuseum.org.uk/on-line/fusion/images/i_jet-t3-s.jpg"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
======================================<br>
<br>
This is the planned &quot;ITER&quot; reactor. Note image of person for scale. {It is still 2 bombs/year/square yard):<br>
---<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.iter.org/ITERPublic/ITER/gifs/iter8x.jpg"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
ITER is still small compared to an actual working commercial powerplant.<br>
<br>
=======================================<br>
<br>
<br>
To provide current USA energy consumption would require ~3,300 full size (non-existant) fusion reactors.<br>
<br>
Global energy replacement would require 13,000 fusion reactors.<br>
<br>
Due to energy growth, in 18 years 6,600 additional extra will be needed.<br>
<br>
Within 4 decades of that, another 20,000 would be needed.<br>
<br>
And each capable of producing 2 bombs/year/squareyard<br>
<br>
===========================================<br>
<br>
Your last point, &quot;Of course fusion isn't practical yet&quot;, true..<br>
