<br>
This statement from the article, provided by Yales, when taken out of the fearmongering blather it was drowning in, makes sense.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Denuclearisation is steamrolling right along.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
This one by Yales is purely wishful thinking. Despite decades of scare tactics the environmental movement has not cleansed the Earth of nuclear power. Partly because their predictions of Armageddon always fall flat. The Denuclearisation movement is dying in my opinion. It cannot be said to be on track or increasing its influence over policy makers. The steam roller(more of a rusty bicycle) is slowing down. In fact it looks likely to get bogged and left behind as those sincerely wanting a cleaner Earth come over to the Pro-nuclear camp. <br>
<br>
I do agree that Fusion would be more dangerous than nuclear power however. Not that this is cause to abandon research into it. A fusion bomb is the twin sword edge of having unlimited free electricity. All technology can serve as a weapon.<br>
<br>
Since the first known accident over a hundred years ago, 25 million people have died because of cars. This arguably places Henry Ford responsible for more human death and misery than has been attributed to Ghenghis Khan, Attila the Hun, Hitler and every other Dictator or Murderer throughout recorded history.<br>
<br>
If we had seen ahead and predicted this suffering then had the power to ban automobile technology over a hundred years ago, would we have? Should we have? Would 25 million lives have been saved and would our lives be better for having suppressed this technology? Who knows? Who cares? Science should not be dictated by 'ifs' and 'maybes'. If it was then we would never have even learned to use fire. Elders would have banned stick rubbing combustion technology the second somebody's house burned down. Risks have to be taken if you want to go forward. Safety only comes with familiarity of a technology. It must be hard won by experience. Not hard won then thrown away. That is the road to regression. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uyales.showPublicProfile?language=EN>yales</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 789<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/11/02 6:58 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=60.topic&index=24>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/53invad2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/fry1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: The Bottom Line.</span><hr size=1> Not true.<br>
