<br>
Prototypes and early models are almost always clumsy... it's interesting how technology follows evolutionary theory... it just gets better and better with each new and improved version.  Look at first generation computers that filled entire rooms, yet today a wrist watch has more processing power.  Now, some older people will say 'they don't make cars like they used to!'  That's a valid statement if you are refering to the 1/4 inch thick sheet metal they used from melted down surplus tanks from WWII!  Modern cars are more fuel efficient, safer, and much more reliable today... my car has over 240,000 miles on it (I bought it new in 198<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START 8) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/glasses.gif ALT="8)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  and it is still running great (and it's American made, believe it or not).<br>
<br>
The point is, at one time in history it was common 'knowledge' that man would never fly... we really shouldn't make any assumptions that something can't be done just because it's what most believe at the moment...  <br>
